RR Team. 
Erin M. Buchanan, PhD, Alexa R. Schlyfestone, Raquel Huggins
Harrisburg University of Science and Technology
Claim Summary.
This replication tests the claim that students with high levels of psychological distress have the least motivation for distance learning. The claim was tested with multinomial logistic regression on psychological distress severity and motivation for distance learning. 
Replication Criteria.
Criteria for a successful replication attempt for the SCORE project is a statistically significant effect (alpha = .05, two tailed) in the same pattern as the original study on the focal hypothesis test (H*). For this study, a successful replication is a statistically significant inverse relationship between severe psychological distress and motivation for distance learning.
Replication Result.
The replication included 733 students with complete data for focal items, which was more than our target analytic sample size (n = 596). The multinominal logistic regression showed a significant effect for the severe distress category, z = -5.77, p = 7.819e-09. In order to determine if this result was in the same direction as the original, the Odds Ratio was calculated: 0.47, 95% CI[0.36, 0.60]. This value is nearly identical to the original value [OR=0.45, P<0.0001, 95% CI: 0.28-0.7], indicating the replication of the claim was successful. See bolded table below. 
Coefficient table:

Deviations from preregistration.
The analyses were incorrectly coded in the preregistration, as it was unclear which variables were categorized from reviewing the paper. The motivation scale is presented as categorical, but was treated as continuous for purposes of analysis, which became clear after the analysis was examined. Additionally, the Kessler scale was made categorical. These were switched in the preregistered analysis, which was fixed in the updated analysis. 
Other additions to the code include:
Deidentification 
Addition of information provided by prolific participants
Exclusion of test surveys that are included in the full data download
Added a few clarifying lines to follow the code procedure (i.e., showed the number of values changing)
Added a line determining final sample size
No deviations were made for the study delivery. 
Description of materials provided.
Methods and Materials: https://osf.io/c3hzb/ 
The AlTammemi_Survey excel file includes the formr coding to create the survey. This format includes all the items and answer choices, which allows recreation of the survey by uploading into formr. 
The Materials document file represents the items shown to participants as a word document that was submitted to the IRB. 
Data: https://osf.io/h7wd5/
AlTammemi_DataDictionary excel file includes a data dictionary for the dataset with all variables explained and choice numbers identified. 
AlTammemi_Survey_deidentify csv file includes the deidentified data. This data was simply processed to exclude Prolific ID numbers, which are not anonymous. You can see the code that created the new column and dropped the Prolific ID column in our Analysis folder. 
AlTammemi_Survey_example csv file is an example dataset that was used to provide preregistration code. 
Analysis: https://osf.io/38wku/
The Analysis rmd (R markdown) and html file are the original preregistered scripts that provided an outline for the analysis.
The Analysis_updated rmd and html file are the updated analysis scripts with the fixed analysis and new code described above. This file can be used to recreate our analyses. Note, you will need to download the full OSF structure to recreate these analyses, as we incorporated the file structure into our script (i.e., it is expected that the markdown file is in a folder Analysis and the data is in a folder Data). Note that the versions of R and packages are provided at the top of the html report for full reproducibility. 
All materials will be made public.
Citation.
